  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential Prison Sentences\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- More severe sentences if linked to other criminal activities\n- Potential enhanced penalties for repeat offenses\n\n2. Financial Penalties\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Potentially up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction\n\n3. Asset Forfeiture\n- Government can seize assets connected to laundered funds\n- Property, bank accounts, and other financial instruments may be confiscated\n\n4. Additional Consequences\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential immigration consequences for non-citizens\n\n5. Civil Penalties\n- Potential additional civil litigation\n- Monetary sanctions from regulatory agencies\n\nThe specific penalties depend on factors like:\n- Amount of money involved\n- Specific circumstances of the offense\n- Prior criminal history\n- Whether the laundering was connected to other criminal activities\n\nProsecution typically occurs under statutes like the Bank Secrecy Act and Money Laundering Control Act.\n\nThese are general overview details. For specific legal advice about a particular situation, consulting a qualified criminal defense attorney is recommended.",
